census_race_labels <- 
  c(
    "White Alone",
    "Black or African American",
    "American Indian and Alaska Native Alone",
    "Asian Alone",
    "Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander Alone)",
    "Some Other Race Alone",
    "Two or More Races"
  )
Alameda_county_education_race <-
  1:7 %>% 
  map_dfr(function(x){
    getCensus(
      name = "acs/acs5",
      vintage = 2018,
      region = "county:001",
      regionin = "state:06",
      vars = paste0("group(C15002",LETTERS[x],")")
    ) %>%
      select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
      pivot_longer(
        ends_with("E"),
        names_to = "variable",
        values_to = "estimate"
      ) %>%
      left_join(
        acs_vars_2018_5yr %>% 
          select(name, label), 
        by = c("variable" = "name")
      ) %>% 
      select(-variable) %>% 
      separate(
        label,
        into = c(NA,NA, "sex", "educational_attainment"),
        sep = "!!"
      ) %>% 
      filter(!is.na(educational_attainment)) %>% 
      mutate(race = census_race_labels[x])
  })
Alameda_race_total <-
  Alameda_county_education_race %>%
  group_by(race) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>%
  mutate(educational_attainment = "Total")


Alameda_county_education_race %>% 
  group_by(educational_attainment, race) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  rbind(Alameda_race_total) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(
    aes(
      x = educational_attainment %>% 
        factor(levels = c(Alameda_county_education_race$educational_attainment[1:4], "Total")),
      y = estimate,
      fill = race
    ),
    stat = "identity",
    position = "stack",
  ) +
  labs(
    x = "Educational Attainment Level",
    y = "Number of Individuals 25 Years or Older",
    title = "Alameda County Educational Attainment by race",
    fill = "Race of Individual"
  ) +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.direction = "vertical"
  )

Alameda_county_education_race %>%
  group_by(educational_attainment, race) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
  rbind(Alameda_race_total) %>%

      x = educational_attainment %>%

((Alameda_county_education_race %>%

((Alameda_county_education_race %>%
    filter(educational_attainment 
           %in% Alameda_county_education_race$educational_attainment[4]) %>%
    filter(race != "White Alone") %>%
    pull(estimate) %>%
    sum()) /
    (Alameda_county_education_race %>%
       filter(educational_attainment 
              %in% Alameda_county_education_race$educational_attainment[4]) %>%
       pull(estimate) %>%
       sum()) * 100) %>%
    round()
## [1] 52
#Non-White individuals make up only 52% of those with a "bachelor's degree or higher."

This analysis indicates that there are disparities between races and educational attainment in Alameda County (for individuals 25 years or older). More specifically, residents who are “White Alone” or “Asian Alone” are overrepresented in the highest educational attainment level and are underrepresented in the lower educational attainment levels. Conversely, residents who are “Black of African American” or “Some Other Race Alone” are underrepresented in the highest educational attainment level and are overrepresented in the lower educational attainment levels. While the overall population of Alameda County is 56% non-White, the subpopulation of individuals without a bachelor’s degree or higher is 60% non-White. Moreover, non-White Individuals make up only 52% of those with a bachelor’s degree or higher. This analysis suggests that there is disproportionate educational attainment by race in Alameda County.

ca_pums <- get_pums(
  variables = c(
    "PUMA",

ca_counties <- counties("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

Alameda_county <-
  ca_counties %>%
  filter(NAME == "Alameda")
ca_pumas <-
  pumas("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

Alameda_pumas <-
  ca_pumas %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  .[Alameda_county, ] %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  left_join(ca_pumas %>% select(GEOID10)) %>% 
  st_as_sf()

Alameda_pums <-
  ca_pums %>% 
  filter(PUMA %in% Alameda_pumas$PUMACE10) %>%
  mutate(SCHG = as.numeric(SCHG)) %>%
  filter(SCHG %in% c(2:14)) %>%
  mutate(
  num_students_no_internet = ifelse(
    (ACCESS == "3"),
    PWGTP,
    0
  ))
student_internet <-
  Alameda_pums %>%
  summarize(
    perc_students_no_internet =
      sum(num_students_no_internet, na.rm = T)/sum(PWGTP, na.rm = T) * 100,
    total_student_no_internet =sum(num_students_no_internet, na.rm =T)
  ) %>%
  print(student_internet)

grouped_by_puma <- 
  Alameda_pums %>%
  group_by(PUMA) %>%
  summarize(
    perc_students_no_internet =
      sum(num_students_no_internet, na.rm = T)/sum(PWGTP, na.rm = T) * 100,
    total_student_no_internet =sum(num_students_no_internet, na.rm =T)
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    Alameda_pumas %>% 
      select(PUMACE10),
    by = c("PUMA" = "PUMACE10")
  ) %>% 
  st_as_sf() 
 

pums_pal <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "Oranges",
  domain = grouped_by_puma$perc_students_no_internet
)

leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>% 
  addPolygons(
    data = grouped_by_puma %>%
       st_transform(4326),
    fillColor = ~pums_pal(perc_students_no_internet),
    color = "white",
    opacity = 0.5,
    fillOpacity = 0.5,
    weight = 1,
    label = ~paste0(
      round(perc_students_no_internet), 
      "% of Students Grades K-12 Without Home Internet Access in ",
      PUMA
    ),
    highlightOptions = highlightOptions(
      weight = 2,
      opacity = 1
    )
  ) %>% 
  addLegend(
    data = grouped_by_puma,
    pal = pums_pal,
    values = ~perc_students_no_internet,
    title = "% of Students Grades K-12 <br> Without Home Internet Access"
  )

One important assumption in this analysis is that the data provides an accurate representation of students’ current situation in Alameda County. Because this analysis is based on ACS 2018 1-year data, it doesn’t capture the affects of the COVID-19 pandemic on remote learning. This data set also doesn’t provide direct insight into additional challenges with remote learning and internet such as the quality of internet access. For example, with more people both working and learning from home, it seems likely that households with internet access could still experience additional internet constraints such as bandwidth issues, and these types of challenges are not reflected in this data set. Moreover, internet access is only valuable to students if they have a device, such as a laptop, to utilize for school work. So, access to an electronic device in addition to internet is another assumption made in this analysis.

Despite these assumptions, this analysis still shows that remote learning is leaving students behind. While the percentage of students grades K-12 without home internet access is ~2.4%, that’s still upwards of 6,000 students who are facing additional challenges to remote learning because they lack internet access. These are challenging times for everyone, students and working adults alike, but these this analysis shows that the challenges are not equal for everyone. This is especially the case for students living in PUMA 00104, where 12% of students grades K-12 lack home internet access. This is ~5X the overall percentage for Alameda County, highlighting that students in particular PUMAS are facing serious obstacles to remote learning.

acs_vars_2019_1yr <-
  listCensusMetadata(
    name = "2019/acs/acs1",
    type = "variables"
  )
ac_mobility_current_19 <-
    getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2019,
    region = "county:001",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07009)")
  ) %>% 
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>% 
      select(name, label), 
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>% 
  select(-variable) %>%
  separate(
    label, 
    into=c(NA,NA,"mobility", "educational_attainment"),
    sep= "!!"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    mobility = ifelse(
      mobility %in% c("Same house 1 year ago:", "Moved within same county:"),
      "Here since last year",
      "Inflow"
    )
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(educational_attainment)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, educational_attainment) %>%
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))
ac_mobility_lastyear_19 <- 
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2019,
    region = "county:001",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07409)")
  ) %>% 
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>% 
      select(name, label), 
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>% 
  select(-variable) %>% 
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility", "educational_attainment"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    mobility = ifelse(
      mobility %in% c("Same house:", "Moved within same county:"),
      "Here since last year",
      "Outflow"
    )
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(educational_attainment)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, educational_attainment) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))
ac_mobility_current_18 <- 
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs1",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "county:001",
    regionin = "state:06",
    vars = c("group(B07009)")
  ) %>% 
  select(!c(GEO_ID,state,NAME) & !ends_with(c("EA","MA","M"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    ends_with("E"),
    names_to = "variable",
    values_to = "estimate"
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    acs_vars_2019_1yr %>% 
      select(name, label), 
    by = c("variable" = "name")
  ) %>% 
  select(-variable) %>% 
  separate(
    label,
    into = c(NA,NA,"mobility", "educational_attainment"),
    sep = "!!"
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    mobility = "Here last year"
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(educational_attainment)) %>%
  group_by(mobility, educational_attainment) %>% 
  summarize(estimate = sum(estimate))
ac_migration_flow_19 <-
   rbind(
    ac_mobility_current_18,
    ac_mobility_lastyear_19 %>% 
      filter(mobility == "Outflow"),
    ac_mobility_current_19 %>% 
      filter(mobility == "Inflow"),
    ac_mobility_current_19 %>% 
      group_by(educational_attainment) %>% 
      summarize(estimate = sum(estimate)) %>% 
      mutate(mobility = "Here this year")
  ) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = mobility,
    values_from = estimate
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    `External net` = Inflow - Outflow,
    `Internal net` = `Here this year` - `Here last year` - `External net`,
     educational_attainment = educational_attainment %>% factor(levels = c(
      "Less than high school graduate",
      "High school graduate (includes equivalency)",
      "Some college or associate's degree",
      "Bachelor's degree",
      "Graduate or professional degree"))
    ) %>%
  arrange(educational_attainment) %>%
  select(
    `Educational Attainment` = educational_attainment,
    `Internal net`,
    `External net`,
    `Here last year`, 
    `Here this year`, 
    Outflow, 
    Inflow
  ) 
 
  
ac_migration_flow_19

The results of this migration analysis show that there is a positive external net flow for the highest education levels (bachelor’s degree or graduate/professional degree). Interestingly, there is also a positive net external flow for people in the “less than high school graduate” category, but this is largely outweighed by the positive external flow of college-educated residents, especially those with a bachelor’s degree. There is a negative external net flow for those in the “high school graduate” or “some college or associate’s degree” category. This division among education levels points to an interesting trend: overall, Alameda county is gaining mostly college-educated residents and losing residents with lower education levels. Similarly, there is a large positive internal net flow in the “bachelor’s degree” and “graduate or professional degree” categories, and this trend is especially large for the “bachelor’s degree” category. This analysis indicates that many residents already living in Alameda County are becoming more educated and thus leaving their old educational attainment categories.

Overall, this analysis shows that the residents of Alameda County have become increasingly educated. The large internal and external net flow of college-educated residents, particularly those with a bachelor’s degree, suggest that the college demographics of of the area play a large role in this trend, as Alameda County has major college cities like Berkeley and Hayward. This trend, however, poses the question of what happens to residents with lower education levels. While many people are increasing their education level internally, this analysis also shows that residents with lower education levels are also leaving the county. This indicates that there are likely negative repercussions of upward educational mobility on less educated residents that are driving them to leave, such as gentrification.
